<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">31665873</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2020</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2020</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>20</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1827-1928</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>60</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2020</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The Journal of sports medicine and physical fitness</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Med Phys Fitness</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effect of caffeine supplementation on exercise performance, power, markers of muscle damage, and perceived exertion in trained CrossFit men: a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled crossover trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>181</StartPage><EndPage>188</EndPage><MedlinePgn>181-188</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.23736/S0022-4707.19.10043-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Caffeine is a popular nutritional supplement among athletes. It is frequently used as an ergogenic aid to improve physical performance, delay fatigue, and increase muscle power. However, these effects have not been tested in CrossFit athletes. The aim of this study was to evaluate the effects of acute caffeine supplementation on workout performance, power, markers of muscle damage, and soreness in trained CrossFit men.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Nine men (28&#xb1;2 years) with experience in CrossFit (2&#xb1;0.3 years) were investigated in a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled crossover trial, with a 7-day washout between treatment periods. The athletes received anhydrous caffeine (CAF: 6 mg/kg body mass) or placebo (PLA) 60 minutes before a CrossFit workout with tasks that involved muscle strength, power, gymnastic movements, and metabolic conditioning. Blood samples were collected for creatine kinase (CK), C-reactive protein, and glucose determination. Workout performance, rating of perceived exertion (RPE), delayed-onset muscle soreness (DOMS), muscle strength (handgrip strength) and power (bench throw, jump squat and countermovement jump) were also evaluated.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">CAF resulted in higher glucose concentration after workout compared to PLA (+3.2 mmol/L, 95% CI: 2.1 to 4.3 vs. +1.5, 95% CI: -0.1 to 3.0 mmol/L, P=0.01). No differences were found between treatments in workout performance, CK, DOMS, RPE, muscle power and strength.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Acute CAF supplementation did not alter performance, markers of muscle damage, power, and RPE in trained CrossFit men.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Foga&#xe7;a</LastName><ForeName>Lorruama J</ForeName><Initials>LJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical and Sports Nutrition Research Laboratory (LABINCE), Faculty of Nutrition, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Santos</LastName><ForeName>Silvia L</ForeName><Initials>SL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical and Sports Nutrition Research Laboratory (LABINCE), Faculty of Nutrition, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Soares</LastName><ForeName>Ronyson C</ForeName><Initials>RC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical and Sports Nutrition Research Laboratory (LABINCE), Faculty of Nutrition, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gentil</LastName><ForeName>Paulo</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Physical Education and Dance, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Naves</LastName><ForeName>Jo&#xe3;o P</ForeName><Initials>JP</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Physical Education and Dance, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dos Santos</LastName><ForeName>Wanderson D</ForeName><Initials>WD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Physical Education and Dance, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Pimentel</LastName><ForeName>Gustavo D</ForeName><Initials>GD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical and Sports Nutrition Research Laboratory (LABINCE), Faculty of Nutrition, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bottaro</LastName><ForeName>Martim</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Physical Education, University of Bras&#xed;lia, Campus Universit&#xe1;rio Darcy Ribeiro, Brasilia, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mota</LastName><ForeName>Jo&#xe3;o F</ForeName><Initials>JF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Clinical and Sports Nutrition Research Laboratory (LABINCE), Faculty of Nutrition, Federal University of Goias, Goiania, Brazil - jfemota@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2019</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>25</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Italy</Country><MedlineTA>J Sports Med Phys Fitness</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>0376337</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0022-4707</ISSNLinking>